post_text:
Hello HVRHS Students and Families!

The school year is almost upon us and, like you, we are getting ready.

Will you help us?

One thing we are doing to get ready is making some videos.

This is where we need help from YOU!

We want students to be a part of welcoming everyone back to school. If you are willing to participate in our Region One is Back! Video, please click the link below to access our Flipgrid- which will collect the videos, and has directions for what to do.

We would love to have as many students involved as possible, but we need to put everything together, so we are asking you to submit any video message you want to share no later than Friday, August 21.

https://flipgrid.com/d4f6d8d9

We can't wait to see your smiling faces!

post_text: This is an incredible synthesis of Ted Perotti's experience, from growing up in Region 1 in a family with deep roots in North Canaan and the trades to learning about film at HVRHS and going on to study it in depth at Endicott College. This is Ted's Senior Thesis Epic in Fulfillment of his Bachelor's of Science in Digital Media with a Concentration in Digital Film from the School of Communications, and it is a fascinating profile of several members of our community. Enjoy!

post_text: Congrats to Brianna Webb & Jessy Haggard, who were awarded 1st Place in the 'Art' category of this year's Braindance Awards from the Inst. of Living @ Hartford Hospital. This annual competition involves students in the process of reducing stigma associated with mental illness and increasing their awareness of careers in fields dedicated to mental health research and treatment. During a curricular unit that included Ken Kesey's One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest, Brianna and Jessy developed a children's book that encourages young people to speak with trusted adults about feelings they cannot name or process and to seek help during those periods in life when they sense something is not right. Together, they were awarded a $500 prize for their submission.

post_text:
Big News, CT students! Debt-Free College was officially announced over the holidays and is now referred to as PACT "Pledge to Advance Connecticut" As of the fall 2020 semester, the State of Connecticut will pay the tuition and fees for students who:
- are CT residents
- have graduated from a CT high school
- will START their college career (after HS graduation) at a CT community college
- apply for FAFSA (regardless of income)
- attend as full-time students
- register for classes by July 15th

See your School Counselor for more details. We will be meeting with seniors soon to explain how this could impact the college process.
